This paper focuses on designing effective ConvNet architectures for action recognition in videos and learning these models given limited training samples. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of good practices in learning ConvNets on video data, which suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of visualization techniques to demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed approach, which suggests that it may belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. The paper involves the study of principles for effective action recognition, which suggests that it may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of temporal structure modeling, which suggests that it may also belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category.
